1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,870
There are times when a data cleric can't download files from the Internet

2
00:00:03,870 --> 00:00:07,800
manually or wants a way to do this more efficiently programmatically.

3
00:00:07,800 --> 00:00:10,470
Let's take a look at a couple of methods where we can use

4
00:00:10,470 --> 00:00:14,175
programmatic approaches towards data gathering to make this more efficient.

5
00:00:14,175 --> 00:00:16,245
We're going to use the Request Library,

6
00:00:16,245 --> 00:00:21,105
which is an HTTP library in Python that allows you to send HTTP requests easily.

7
00:00:21,105 --> 00:00:23,925
Let's see an example of an HTTP request.

8
00:00:23,925 --> 00:00:25,570
This is a GET request,

9
00:00:25,570 --> 00:00:27,980
which is used to request data from a source,

10
00:00:27,980 --> 00:00:30,195
like a URL from Wikipedia.

11
00:00:30,195 --> 00:00:34,605
How do we know whether or not our request to get data from a URL has succeeded?

12
00:00:34,605 --> 00:00:37,195
There are status codes that help us with that.

13
00:00:37,195 --> 00:00:40,250
Codes between 200 and 299 indicate that

14
00:00:40,250 --> 00:00:43,475
the request was successful and we got the data that we needed.

15
00:00:43,475 --> 00:00:48,160
On the other hand, codes between 400-599 indicate errors.

16
00:00:48,160 --> 00:00:51,290
You've probably encountered the infamous 404 error

17
00:00:51,290 --> 00:00:54,080
when trying to access a website that no longer exists.

18
00:00:54,080 --> 00:00:57,140
The requests library enables us to catch these errors to

19
00:00:57,140 --> 00:01:00,925
understand when and why our programmatic requests fail.

20
00:01:00,925 --> 00:01:04,235
Let's now take a look at how to do this in Python.

21
00:01:04,235 --> 00:01:07,850
Let's take a brief look at how to use the request library to make an

22
00:01:07,850 --> 00:01:11,825
HTTP get request to programmatically download files from the Internet.

23
00:01:11,825 --> 00:01:17,105
For this demo, we're leveraging some movie reviews written by Roger Ebert in 2017.

24
00:01:17,105 --> 00:01:21,460
Our first step is import the libraries that we're going to be using, requests and os.

25
00:01:21,460 --> 00:01:24,875
Then we're going to go ahead and create a directory using

26
00:01:24,875 --> 00:01:29,860
os.makedirs where we can store the files that we're going to programmatically download.

27
00:01:29,860 --> 00:01:33,410
Note that we're going to create this directory if it doesn't already exist by

28
00:01:33,410 --> 00:01:37,900
using os.path.exists to check whether or not the file path already exists.

29
00:01:37,900 --> 00:01:43,685
Next, we've predefined a list of URLs of existing reviews.

30
00:01:43,685 --> 00:01:46,855
Let's dive into the requests code.

31
00:01:46,855 --> 00:01:49,350
For each of the URLs in this list,

32
00:01:49,350 --> 00:01:53,720
we're going to go ahead and create a HTTP GET request using the

33
00:01:53,720 --> 00:01:57,230
request.get(url) and then use the raise_for_status function to

34
00:01:57,230 --> 00:02:00,790
raise an exception if this GET request is resulting in an error.

35
00:02:00,790 --> 00:02:04,940
Then we're going to construct the file path for saving the content we'll download.

36
00:02:04,940 --> 00:02:07,415
We're going to combine the folder name that we defined

37
00:02:07,415 --> 00:02:10,265
earlier and the last part of the URL.

38
00:02:10,265 --> 00:02:13,205
For example, for this first URL that we've got here,

39
00:02:13,205 --> 00:02:20,630
the file path would be ebert_reviews_2017/1-the-wizard-of-oz-1939-film.txt.

40
00:02:20,630 --> 00:02:23,900
Then here we're simply using Python's open function

41
00:02:23,900 --> 00:02:28,430
to open the file specified by the file path in the binary write mode.

42
00:02:28,430 --> 00:02:30,845
Why WB or binary mode?

43
00:02:30,845 --> 00:02:34,280
Because the content of the response object that we're writing

44
00:02:34,280 --> 00:02:37,940
here to the file retrieved from the URL is in bytes.

45
00:02:37,940 --> 00:02:43,410
Finally, this file.write function is actually writing the binary content to the file.

46
00:02:44,210 --> 00:02:47,505
It suceeded on the first three URLs,

47
00:02:47,505 --> 00:02:49,740
but our code is failing on our fourth URL.

48
00:02:49,740 --> 00:02:51,195
This is intentional.

49
00:02:51,195 --> 00:02:56,675
Note how our URL here is erroneously specifying Bumblebee as part of the URL.

50
00:02:56,675 --> 00:03:02,285
We can see how the requests library is immediately raising a 403 client error,

51
00:03:02,285 --> 00:03:05,735
indicating the client is forbidden from accessing a valid URL.

52
00:03:05,735 --> 00:03:09,830
For the other three URLs that we were able to save successfully,

53
00:03:09,830 --> 00:03:11,660
through the os.listdir command,

54
00:03:11,660 --> 00:03:15,775
we can actually check to see that these were successfully saved to our directory.

55
00:03:15,775 --> 00:03:19,760
We can also use the built-in so-called magic command to actually load one of

56
00:03:19,760 --> 00:03:21,710
these reviews into the current cell in

57
00:03:21,710 --> 00:03:24,900
our Jupyter notebook to see that we were successful.

